b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\n\n\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC " -//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\n<workbook_page id="p4_percent_yields" xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/"\n    xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/" xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/"\n    xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\n    xmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/">\n\n\n    <head>\n        <title>Percent Yield</title>\n        <objref idref="percent_yield"/>\n\n    </head>\n\n    <body>\n\n        <section id="p4_percent_yields_DE1">\n            <title></title>\n            <body><p>The amount of product that may be produced by a reaction under specified conditions, as\n            calculated per the stoichiometry of an appropriately balanced chemical equation, is\n            called the <extra><anchor>theoretical yield</anchor><meaning><material><p>amount of product that may be produced from a given amount of reactant(s) according to the reaction stoichiometry</p></material></meaning></extra> of the reaction. In practice, the amount of product\n            obtained is called the <extra><anchor>actual yield</anchor><meaning><material><p>amount of product formed in a reaction</p></material></meaning></extra>, and it is often less than the theoretical yield for\n            a number of reasons. Some reactions are inherently inefficient, being accompanied by\n            side reactions that generate other products. Some products are difficult to collect\n            without some loss, and so less than perfect recovery will reduce the actual yield. The\n            extent to which a reaction\xe2\x80\x99s theoretical yield is achieved is commonly expressed as its\n            <extra><anchor>percent yield</anchor><meaning><material><p>measure of the efficiency of a reaction, expressed as a percentage of the theoretical yield</p></material></meaning></extra>.</p>\n        <image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"></image>\n        <dl>\n            <dt><em>Percent Yield</em></dt>\n            <dd><formula>$$\\mathrm{percent}\\;\\mathrm{yield}\\;=\\;\\frac{\\mathrm{actual}\\;\\mathrm{yield}}{\\mathrm{theoretical}\\;\\mathrm{yield}}\\;\\times\\;100\\%$$</formula></dd>\n            <dd>Actual and theoretical yields may be expressed as masses or molar amounts (or any\n                other appropriate property; e.g., volume, if the product is a gas). As long as both\n                yields are expressed using the same units, these units will cancel when percent\n                yield is calculated.</dd>\n        </dl>\n        <image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"></image></body></section>\n        <example id="p4_percent_yields_EX1">\n            <p>Upon reaction of 1.274 g of copper sulfate with excess zinc metal, 0.392 g copper\n                metal was obtained according to the equation:</p>\n            <formula>$${\\mathrm{CuSO}}_4(aq)\\;+\\;\\mathrm{Zn}(s)\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;\\mathrm{Cu}(s)\\;+\\;{\\mathrm{ZnSO}}_4(aq)$$</formula>\n\n\n            <p>What is the percent yield?</p>\n\n            <p>The provided information identifies copper sulfate as the limiting reactant. The\n                amount of product produced by the limiting reactant is the theoretical yield.</p>\n            <formula>$$\\require{cancel}1.274\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm\n                g\\;{\\mathrm{CuSO}}_4}\\;\\times\\;\\frac{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm{CuSO}}_4}}{159.62\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm\n                g\\;{\\mathrm{CuSO}}_4}}\\;\\times\\;\\frac{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{Cu}}}{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm{CuSO}}_4}}\\;\\times\\;\\frac{63.55\\;\\mathrm\n                g\\;\\mathrm{Cu}}{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{Cu}}}\\;=\\;0.5072\\;\\mathrm\n                g\\;\\mathrm{Cu}\\;$$</formula>\n\n\n\n            <p>Using this theoretical yield and the provided value for actual yield, the percent\n                yield is calculated to be</p>\n\n            <formula>$$\\mathrm{percent}\\;\\mathrm{yield}\\;=\\;\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{actual}\\;\\mathrm{yield}\\;\\;}{\\mathrm{theoretical}\\;\\mathrm{yield}}\\right)\\;\\times\\;100\\%$$</formula>\n            <formula>$$\\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm{percent}\\;\\mathrm{yield}\\;=\\;\\left(\\frac{0.392\\;\\mathrm\n                g\\;\\mathrm{Cu}\\;}{0.5072\\;\\mathrm\n                g\\;\\mathrm{Cu}}\\right)\\;\\times\\;100\\%\\\\\\\\\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;=\\;77.3\\%\\end{array}$$</formula>\n          \n        </example>\n        <wb:inline idref="percentyield_lbd1b703c82d38844509abda3388bac5c151" purpose="learnbydoing"></wb:inline>\n        <wb:inline idref="percentyield_lbd2c595e18dcf5f4205b69bddf2803486dd" purpose="learnbydoing"></wb:inline>\n        <wb:inline idref="percentyield_lbd3abbff7a1c5b948a7a51e17cae430d966" purpose="learnbydoing"></wb:inline>\n        \n        <wb:inline idref="percentyield_digt" purpose="didigetthis"></wb:inline>\n                <p>Adapted from <link href="https://cnx.org/contents/havxkyvS@9.422:b39avmGq@29/Preface"\n                >Openstax Chemistry</link> under <link\n                href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/"> Creative Commons Attribution\n                4.0 License. </link></p>\n        <p>Download for free at <link\n                href="http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312"\n                >http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312.</link></p>\n\n\n\n    </body>\n</workbook_page>\n'